AGI - "Francesco, I and other family members thank you for the many manifestations of affection, closeness and comfort >. I did not have the strength to respond before and to the many messages, because the pain is too great." Thus begins a long social post by Mario Occhiuto, > senator of FI and father of Francesco, the <a href="https://www.agi.it/cronaca/news/2025-02-22/morto-son-child-30133729/"> thirty-year-old researchers who died last Friday </a> after falling from a window of his home.
<br> "We have spent the last two years together. He traveled and lived with me in Rome to follow his research contract with the University, and in the rest of the week he began to practice his psychologist > and attend the course of psychotherapy. Everything with its simplicity, essentiality, sweetness and goodness of mind - the memory of the political exponent - read a lot, loved to reflect, to question the true meaning of life. You can't imagine how special it was. He had only one dream, one project: to help those who were ill>. Because he knew what it meant. He silently fought an inner battle, > against those destortive thoughts that assaulted him. And in this he was very good: he could not leak anything outside."
&nbsp;
<div </div
<br> "With me, however, sometimes you let go a little more. He trusted, and together we tried to find a way to lighten that weight. With the help of some specialists we tried to improve things, and for a while it seemed like we had succeeded. We went together in the car to Lourdes,» to find the Madonnina, in the hope that he gave us help, an answer, a little peace. I thought I could protect him. I thought we'd do it. But not," he adds.
<br> "I hope with all my heart that this pain has a sense > and that, to welcome it, there is a Paradise. Because if there is someone who deserves it, it is he - concludes Occhiuto - to us remains an uncultivated vacuum. >And to me, also the certainty that the last two years beside him were the most beautiful, the most intense, the most true of my life. Every hug filled me with an infinite joy. Now everything seems to me suspended, without direction. I feel emptied, like life lost its sense. If it wasn't for those who still need me, I don't know how I could move on. But that doesn't matter and I know I have to. Thanks again to everyone for making us feel less alone in this pain that will never end."&nbsp;
