AGI - "I wish this city every luck. We need to be careful to select the ruling class because then it is not always easy to perform the many complex miracles that we have accomplished in these years in this continuous climate of divisions and aggression. This division, this continuous schizophrenia, endemic, is what then allows other intelligences, to other powers, to Bari and Rome, to always overwhelm the interests of this territory. We never learn the lesson." This was said by the mayor of Taranto, Rinaldo Melucci, after the formalization of the resignation by the majority of municipal councilors who will determine the dissolution of the council.
&nbsp;
The resignation is irrevocable. Municipal councillors this morning deposited and signed the 17 signatures necessary to initiate the early dissolution procedure of the municipal council and therefore the decadence of the administration. "We could no longer tolerate the inability in the management of the municipal machine now impantanata, which has caused the commissariamento of the Municipality on the Mediterranean Games, arrived because of the inertia of those who guided the Municipality" says the Pd of Taranto with Anna Filippetti and Giuseppe Tursi. And for Brothers of Italy, Congressman Dario Iaia says: "We remind those who today want to remake an image that failed was not only the former mayor, but the political project of the Democratic Party and the M5S. Both, in fact, supported Melucci and shared the actions of the latter, participating in the choices adopted and the prebenda of the armchairs".
E Massimiliano Di Cuia, Regional Councillor of Forza Italia, states: "Today is an important day for Taranto: the Melucci administration fell after a long agony that prevented the municipal junta to start any useful initiative to the community. A immobilism that forced us opposition counselors to perform a strong act, but we had no alternative." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
The story is repeated, therefore, for Melucci, ex Pd. As already happened in November 2021, this time he will be forced to leave Palazzo di Città. Already last year the councilmen tried to send him home with the same system, but they did not hit the result because he eventually missed a signature. Melucci was re-elected mayor in June 2022 with 60 percent of the votes (the first election dates back to June 2017). Then he was at Pd's altitude and he led a center-left alliance.
Then he left the Pd and also his majority changed political sign. I Dem left. In the second term, Melucci only made halfway, because he was central and central, with a maneuver maybe long thought but set up in the last few hours, they joined and sent him home at a time. To the representatives of the two sides who had collected 15 signatures, two councillors were added out of the majority of the mayor, Vittorio Mele and Michele Patano, and this allowed to reach the 17 signatures. That later became 19 because also two other councilmen of the majority of the mayor, the former Italy Viva Massimiliano Stellato and the former pentastellato Mario Odone.
&nbsp;
Aver signed the signatures before February 24, should allow Taranto to have - once formalized the procedure - a short commission and return to the vote already' in this spring. Also for this has been accelerated the collection of signatures, that is to avoid a long administrative holiday, much more than the city - one of the largest of the South - is to take with complex matches: from the sale of the former Ilva to the Games of the Mediterranean of 2026, from the crisis of the port and the new governance of the Harbour Authority to the choice of Taranto as priority hub, together with Augusta, for the construction of the great structures of the offshore wind. And then the state of the reclamation, the implementation of the Just Transition Fund (800 million to favour Taranto transition and conversion) and the reboot of the institutional development contract (Cis). In addition to the interweaving of social and economic knots, the municipalities of Taranto, second city of Puglia after Bari, will also cross the regional elections of Puglia that see Michele Emiliano coming out for ten years as governor. &nbsp;
